Incremental Training:

add_vector() - Hooks into each addPoint call, buffering vectors
Automatically retrains when buffer reaches capacity (default: 1000 vectors)
Maintains running sum and count for efficient centroid updates
Thread-safe with mutex for concurrent operations

Persistent Storage:

save() / load() - Store complete state (centroid, running sum, buffer) to disk
Preserves training progress across restarts
Binary format for efficiency

Configurable Retraining:

buffer_capacity - How many vectors to collect before retraining
retrain_interval - Same as buffer_capacity (kept for clarity)
flush_buffer() - Manually trigger retrain at any time

Usage Pattern:

Create index with buffer size (e.g., 1000 vectors)
Each addPoint() feeds into the quantizer
Auto-retrains every N vectors
Periodically save to disk (e.g., every 10k vectors)
Load from disk on restart - continues training where it left off

Benefits:

No separate training phase needed
Centroid adapts to data distribution over time
Minimal overhead - just accumulates sums
Can start with empty index or pre-trained state

The example shows a complete IncrementalBinaryIndex wrapper that handles everything automatically. You just call addPoint() and it manages training, encoding, and indexing behind the scenes!
